HUNDREDS of mourners gathered, 3 July, to say goodbye to two kids and their father, who were allegedly poisoned by their mum. Speakers at the service held at Bohlokong New Hall in Bethlehem, Free State, used the opportunity to demand justice. Two girls, aged 10 and 14, and their father (49) were allegedly given a brown bean soup for breakfast by their mum at their home on Wednesday, 22 June. Their 10-year-old sister is recovering in hospital. Addressing mourners, a family member said there were still many unanswered questions. “It’s difficult to admit we lost our brother and his daughters. Every house has its differences, but poisoning your husband and kids is not the solution,” he said. “What happened to us is a lifetime trauma. Even though we welcome condolences, it will take a million years to forget. We hand everything to law enforcement and we hope justice will prevail, although it will never bring them back.” Dihlabeng Mayor Tseki Tseki said they wanted justice for the victims. encouraged residents to report gender-based violence as early as possible. “We’ve lost young people who might have become the leaders of our municipality. It’s our hope to see justice prevailing against those responsible for this tragedy.” “Gender-based violence is slowly turning out to be our biggest enemy in black communities. We want to send our deepest condolences to the family, friends and the community at large,” he said. The Free Sate Education Department promised to provide the classmates of the children with counselling. The children complained of stomach cramps shortly after arriving at school and were taken to a nearby clinic where they were declared dead. The father died on his way to hospital. It’s alleged the mum admitted to using a poison called Temik to kill her family. She’s facing three charges of murder and one of attempted murder. Her bail application has been postponed to 14 July.